# Maybe we are overthinking this.
#
# For a discrete time MbP, imagine we promote its periodic state update event from discrete to unrestricted, so that we're not limited to plain vectors as our state.  (Any approach that samples the input ports would basically end up doing this anyway, since plenty of the inputs are abstract already.  Not just the stuff like applied spatial forces, but remember that contact surfaces are also part of the input we need to sample.)  Under this assumption, we have abstract state available as a tool.
#
# Next, imagine we change the MbP's state from just `{VectorXd}` (the q,v kinematics) to instead be `{VectorXd, internal::ContactSolverResults}`, and have the update event copy out the SAP solver results into state.
#
# Then, change all of the output ports that currently depend on `EvalContactSolverResults` to depend on the memorized results from the state, instead.
#
# Later: Okay, in the periodic update it looks like it will suffice to memorize:
# - acceleration kinematics cache (7 * num_mobods)
# - contact solver results (2 * num_velocities + 6 * num_contacts)
# - contact surfaces / points
